Housed in what had been an edifice of New York City’s Parks Department, this small way-station accomplishes its purpose. Travellers can refresh themselves, rest (parking for three vehicles) and acquire foodstuffs (bagels, doughnuts, croissants, etc). The foreign employee is friendly. Directly next to this branch of Dunkin’ Donuts is a Citgo has station, and directly across the Hutchinson Parkway is the same arrangement; a D’D next to a Citgo! Wi-fi is free, and there is countertop seating for about three people. The venue recycles, and its bathroom is also environmentally friendly with a hand-blower, though it is somewhat grungy!

Stopped there. Got large ice coffee and donuts. Transaction went fine. Drove for almost an hour. Then realized I'd left my phone there after my friend called and Dunkin Donuts had it. I was annoyed but relieved. Drove 45 min to get back to this Dunkin Donuts expecting a pleasant simple exchange. I was wrong. The same person who sold me the coffee and donuts demanded $25 to return my phone. I laughed but it became clear she was serious. Her rationale wad that a new phone would have cost me $600 or more and that paying her $25 for my phone was more than fair. I got angry but stayed calm and kept saying thank you and may I please have my phone. She said thank you was not enough and demanded $25. When she realized I would not budge she angrily tossed my phone across the counter and said if that happened to me again there I would never get my phone back no matter what. I am so appalled. There were even 2 of her co-workers that were saying "just pay her". When did human kindness shift to extortion?
